Now, because the firm is currently worth $1,040, the value of equity is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Value of Equity}&=\frac{\left(\$1,040-\$896.95\right)}{1.22}\\[20pt]
&=\frac{\$143.05}{1.22}\\[20pt]
&=\boxed{\$117.25}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the value of equity is $117.25.

Then, the value of debt is solved below: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Value of Debt}&=\text{Value of Assets}-\text{Value of Equity}\\[15pt]
&=\$1,040-\$117.25\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{922.75}
\end{aligned}$$

The value of the asset is subtracted by the computed value of equity to determine the value of debt. 

Hence, the value of the debt is $922.75.

